''Mind Over Magic'', ''New Invocation'', ''Seance'', ''Vanish'' and ''Vibrations''.<ref name=\"Magicana\" />\n\n== Ghostwriting ==\n\nRichard made his living as a [[ghostwriter]] for several years and has ghosted 30 books on a wide variety of subjects.<ref>Rainbow News, August/September 1997, page 29</ref>\n\n== Richard Webster Popular Fiction Book Award ==\n\nIn 2000 Webster in conjunction with Hazard Press, established the annual Richard Webster Popular Fiction Award competition, which ran for five years.  The winning author each year received $5,000, plus publication of their winning entry by Hazard Press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.times.co.nz/news/kiwi-anonymous-in-homeland.html|title=Kiwi Anonymous in Homeland, Times, 24 March 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/literature/prizes/richardwebster/index.asp|title=Christchurch City Library : Richard Webster Popular Fiction Award}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/Writers/Profiles/Muller,%20C.%20George|title=NZ Book Council : C. George Muller Biography}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hazardonline.com/awards2002.html|title=Hazard Online : Richard Webster Popular Fiction Award Winners}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\n\nThe Dunninger Memorial Award for Distinguished Professionalism in the Performance of Mentalism. Presented by the Psychic Entertainers Association, June 9, 1990.<ref name=\"p-e-a\">{{cite web|url=http://www.p-e-a.org/awards.html|title=Psychic Entertainers Association : Awards}}</ref>\n\n[[Variety Artists Club of New Zealand]] Scroll of Honour 1994.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://66.147.244.133/~vacorgnz/vac-scrolls-of-honour/|title=Variety Artists Club of NZ Scroll Recipients}}</ref>\n\n[[Variety Artists Club of New Zealand]] Top Specialty Act 1997.\n\nDan Blackwood Memorial Award for Outstanding Contribution to the Art of Mentalism presented by the Psychic Entertainers Association, June 2007.<ref name=\"p-e-a\" />\n\nLifetime Achievement Award in recognition of a lifetime dedicated to excellence in writing magical literature. Presented by Magic New Zealand, December 2008.<ref name=\"aucklandmagicianblog\" />\n\nConvention of Visionary Retailers Visionary Awards - Best Divination Book 2012 - Spirit and Dream Animals by Richard Webster, June 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.covr.org/covr-awards/2012-awards/2012-book-divination/|title=Convention of Visionary Retailers Visionary Awards}}</ref>\n\n[[Grand Master of Magic Award]] presented by the Brotherhood of Auckland Magicians, the Shore City Magicians Club, and the magicians of New Zealand, February 2013.<ref name=\"times\" /><ref name=\"ibmring160\" />\n\nThe Annemann Award for Mentalism presented by Stevens Magic Emporium, Kansas, March 2014.\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.richardwebster.co.nz/ Richard Webster - International Author]\n* [http://www.llewellyn.com/author.php?author_id=2604 Llewellyn Worldwide - Author Profile]\n* [http://www.times.co.nz/news/kiwi-anonymous-in-homeland.html Kiwi Anonymous in Homeland, Times, 24 March 2006]\n* [http://brotherhoodofaucklandmagicians.com/grand-masters-of-magic/#richardwebster Richard Webster : Grand Master of Magic Citation : Brotherhood of Auckland Magicians Club]\n*\n*\n*\n*\n\n<!-- This will add a notice to the bottom of the page and won't blank it! The new template which says that your draft is waiting for a review will appear at the bottom; simply ignore the old (grey) drafted templates and the old (red) decline templates. A bot will update your article submission. Until then, please don't change anything in this text box.  Just press \"Save page\". -->\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Webster, Richard}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male novelists]]\n[[Category:People educated at King's College, Auckland]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand novelists]]\n[[Category:Mentalists]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name        = Richard Webster\n| image       = Richardwebsternewzealandauthor.jpg\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_date  = December 9, 1946\n| birth_place = [[Auckland]], New Zealand\n| death_date  =\n| death_place =\n| occupation  = Author, Ghostwriter, Entertainer\n| website     = http://www.psychic.co.nz/\n| footnotes   =\n}}\n\n'''Richard Webster''' (born December 9, 1946) is an award winning multi-million selling author,<ref name=Times>{{cite web|url=http://www.times.co.nz/news/kiwi-anonymous-in-homeland.html|title=Kiwi Anonymous in Homeland, ''Times'', March 24, 2006}}</ref> [[ghostwriter]], [[mentalist]], [[hypnotist]] and [[magic (illusion)|magician]].<ref name=\"times\">{{cite web|url=http://www.times.co.nz/news/best-magic-moment-of-all-of-them.html|title=Richard Webster Grand Master of Magic, Howick Pakuranga Times Article|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303232350/http://www.times.co.nz/news/best-magic-moment-of-all-of-them.html|archivedate=2016-03-03}}</ref><ref name=\"ibmring160\">{{cite web|url=http://ibmring160.com/national-awards/grand-masters.aspx|title=Grand Master of Magic Recipients}}</ref><ref name=\"aucklandmagicianblog\">{{cite web|url=http://aucklandmagicianblog.com/2013/03/04/richard-webster-grand-master-of-magic/|title=Richard Webster Grand Master of Magic Citation}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.p-e-a.org/awards.html|title=Psychic Entertainers Association: Awards}}</ref>\n\n== Biography ==\n\nRichard Webster was born in [[Auckland]], New Zealand.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3231600150/webster-richard-1946.html|title=Encyclopedia.com Author Biography}}</ref>  He was educated at [[King's School (Auckland)|King's School]] and [[King's College, Auckland|King's College]].  As a child, he wrote and produced a weekly neighbourhood newspaper called ''The Waiochiel'' that he sold to his neighbours.<ref>King's Courier, No. 85, Autumn 2002, pages 14-15</ref>  He worked in publishing for several years before starting his career as a writer, entertainer, and speaker. He initially worked as a ghost writer, and wrote a small book on the subject.<ref>''Secrets of Ghostwriting'', Martin Breese, 1986</ref> He is the author of 112 books, mainly on [[New Age]] topics. He has also written three novels.\n\nHis books have been translated into 29 languages: Bulgarian, Chinese (Simplified), Chinese (Traditional), Croatian, Czech, Danish, Dutch, Estonian, French, German, Greek, Hungarian, Bahasa Indonesia, Italian, Japanese, Korean,  Latvian,  Lithuanian, Polish, Portuguese, Romanian, Russian, Serbian, Slovak, Slovenian,  Spanish, Swedish, Thai and Turkish.<ref>Llewellyn Catalog, Fall 2012</ref>\n\nRainbow News described him as \"one of the most successful writers in the country\".<ref>Rainbow News, August/September 1997</ref> [[New Idea|New Idea magazine]] wrote that Richard is \"probably New Zealand's most successful author\".<ref>''New Idea'', April 28, 2001, page 80</ref>\n\nWebster has appeared on numerous radio and TV programs, including [[Hard Copy]], WMAQ-TV (Chicago), KTLA-TV (Los Angeles), KSTW-TV (Seattle), and [[Mike and Maty]] (ABC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.llewellyn.com/author.php?author_id=2604|title=Llewellyn Worldwide : Richard Webster Author Profile}}</ref> In 1996, he was one of the performers on The Great Kiwi Magic Show on TV3.<ref>Magicana, April/May 2011, page 25</ref>\n\nIn 2000 the Richard Webster Popular Fiction Award was established, with the winner receiving a $5,000 prize and publication of their winning entry.<ref name=Times/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://christchurchcitylibraries.com/literature/prizes/richardwebster/index.asp|title=Christchurch City Library: Richard Webster Popular Fiction Award}}</ref>\n\nWebster is a past president of the New Zealand Society of Magicians. He received the prestigious [[Grand Master of Magic Award]] in February 2013.<ref name=\"times\" /><ref name=\"ibmring160\" />\n\n== Personal ==\n\nRichard is married with three children and five grandchildren.<ref name=\"encyclopedia\" />\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n===Nonfiction===\n\n* ''Freedom to Read'', 1972, HPP Press\n* ''Sun Sign Success'', 1982, Brookfield Press\n* ''The Stars and Your Destiny'', 1982, Brookfield Press\n* ''How to Read Tea Leaves'', 1982, Brookfield Press\n* ''Discovering Numerology'', 1983, Brookfield Press\n* ''How to Read Minds'', 1986, Brookfield Press\n* ''Secrets of Ghostwriting'', 1986, Martin Breese Limited\n* ''How to Develop Your Psychic Power'', 1988, Martin Breese Limited\n* ''Good Luck from Beijing'', 1990, Martin Breese International\n* ''Revealing Hands'', 1994, [[Llewellyn Worldwide|Llewellyn Publications]]. Reprinted as ''The Complete Book of Palmistry'', 2001\n* ''Omens, Oghams and Oracles'', 1995, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Talisman Magic'', 1995, Llewellyn Publications, Reprinted as ''Numerology Magic'', 1998\n* ''Dowsing for Beginners'', 1996, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui for Beginners'', 1997, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Aura Reading for Beginners'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Spirit Guides and Angel Guardians'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Astral Travel for Beginners'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Chinese Numerology'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''101 Feng Shui Tips for the Home'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui for the Workplace'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui for Apartment Living'', 1998, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui in the Garden'', 1999, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui for Love and Romance'', 1999, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Feng Shui for Success and Happiness'', 1999, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Palm Reading for Beginners'', 2000, Llewellyn Publications\n* ''Writing as a Business'', 2000, Brookfield Press\n*