{"title_page": "Jack Ross (writer)", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Jack Ross''' (born 6 November 1962 in [[Auckland]]), is a New Zealand poet, novelist, translator, editor and lecturer in creative writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm |title=Jack Ross \u2013 Massey University |work=massey.ac.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616111947/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm |archive-date=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A trilogy of novels has been published by two different publishers, [[Alan Brunton]]'s Bumper Books (Volume 1) and [[Titus Books (publisher)|Titus Books]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on Auckland's [[North Shore City|North Shore]], Ross was raised and educated in the [[East Coast Bays]]. After completing degrees in English and Italian at the [[University of Auckland]], Ross was given a [[Commonwealth Scholarship]] to study in the UK in<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/writers/rossjack.html |title=New Zealand Book Council |work=bookcouncil.org.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref> and was awarded a PhD in English and Comparative Literature by the [[University of Edinburgh]]. He is a Lecturer specialising in Academic and Creative Writing at [[Massey University]]'s Albany campus.\n\nFrom 2002 to 2005 Ross was editor of the literary magazine ''brief''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=757741 |title=brief |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714152326/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=757741 |archive-date=14 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has also edited other literary magazines ''The Pander'' (co-editor 1998\u201399),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=337755 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715141644/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=337755 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2012 |title=The Pander |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 }}</ref> ''Spin'' (co-editor 1999\u20132003),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=452127 |title=Spin : the quarterly magazine of Poetry Orbital Workshops. |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711204655/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=452127 |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Landfall (journal)|Landfall]]'' (guest editor: issue 214, 2007),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/landfall214.html |title=Landfall 212. 'The Capital of Nowhere', Edited by Richard Reeve Otago University Press, New Zealand |work=otago.ac.nz |year=2008 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref> and ''Poetry NZ'' (guest editor: issue 38, 2008).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.poetrynz.net/archives/issue-38/ |title=Poetry New Zealand: Issue 38  |work=poetrynz.net |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nRoss is little known outside New Zealand avante garde literary circles. He was described by [[Richard Reeve (poet)|Richard Reeve]] in ''[[Landfall (journal)|Landfall]]'' as \"a leading contributor to the field of experimental writing in New Zealand\",<ref>http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/forthcomingissue.html</ref> Mark Houlahan remarked in ''New Zealand Books'' [15 (2) (June 2005): 14\u201315], that \"Nobody else in New Zealand writes quite like Ross, though some of [[Bill Manhire]]'s fictions in ''The New Land'' are precedents.\" Other reviewers have been less positive: [[Laurence Jenkins]] wrote that \"Not all the contents are evil, but the spirit of darkness certainly prevails,\" about ''Nights with Giordano Bruno'' [in JAAM 16 (2001): 185]. According to [[Joe Wylie]] \"Outside of literati farm, this sort of thing has a very limited life expectancy ... Can Ross move beyond this? Does he choose not to?\" [Takahe 54 (2005) 63].\n\n==Works==\n* ''City of Strange Brunettes''. {{ISBN|0-473-05446-9}} (Auckland: Pohutukawa Press, 1998) [poems]\n* (with Gabriel White) ''A Town like Parataxis''. {{ISBN|0-473-07104-5}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2000) [poems / photos] [http://mairangibay.blogspot.com/2008/10/town-like-parataxis.html]\n* ''Nights with Giordano Bruno''. {{ISBN|0-9582225-0-9}} (Wellington: Bumper Books, 2000) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 1)] [http://www.crywolfbooks.org/bruno.php]\n* (with Gabriel White) ''The Perfect Storm''. {{ISBN|0-473-07350-1}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2000) [poems / video]\n* ''The Writing Skills Workshop''. prod. Robert van der Vyver (Otago University: Higher Education Development Centre, 2001) [workbook / video]\n* ''Chantal's Book''. {{ISBN|0-473-08744-8}} (Wellington: HeadworX, 2002) [poems] [http://headworx.eyesis.co.nz/poetry/chantal.php]\n* ''Monkey Miss Her Now''. {{ISBN|0-476-00182-X}} (Auckland: Danger Publishing, 2004) [short stories]\n* ''Trouble in Mind''. {{ISBN|0-9582586-1-9}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2005) [novella] [https://web.archive.org/web/20061202010251/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/Trouble.html]\n* ''A Bus Called Mr Nice Guy''. {{ISBN|0-473-10526-8}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2005) [poems / travelogue]\n* ''The Imaginary Museum of Atlantis''. {{ISBN|0-9582586-8-6}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2006) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 2)] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070819044234/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/Atlantis.html]\n* ''To Terez\u00edn''. Social and Cultural Studies, 8. ISSN 1175-7132 (Auckland: Massey University, 2007) [poems / travelogue] [http://readingthemaps.blogspot.com/2007/06/to-terezin-and-back.html]\n*  ''Papyri: Love Poems & Fragments from Sappho''. {{ISBN|978-0-473-12397-0}} (Auckland: Soapbox Press, 2007)\n* ''EMO''. {{ISBN|978-1-877441-07-3}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2008) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 3)]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://titus.books.online.fr/html/EMO.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721015102/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/EMO.html |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''The Return of the Vanishing New Zealander''. {{ISBN|978-0-9864507-6-1}}. (Dunedin: Kilmog Press, 2009) [poems]\n* ''Kingdom of Alt''. {{ISBN|978-1-877441-15-8}}. (Auckland: Titus Books, 2010) [short stories / novella]\n\nJack Ross has also edited and co-edited a number of publications.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* <span id=\"ref_Massey\">University of Massey Staff Page [https://web.archive.org/web/20120616111947/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm \"Jack Ross]\" '</span>\n* <span id=\"ref_RossLandfall\">Landfall Web Page [http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/forthcomingissue.html \"Forthcoming Issue]\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_ReadingTheMaps\">Reading The Maps [http://readingthemaps.blogspot.com/2006/12/more-on-shore.html \"More On Shore]\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_Houlahan\">New Zealand Books 15 (2) (June 2005): 14\u201315\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_Massey\">[[New Zealand Book Council]] [http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/writers/rossjack.html \"Jack Ross]\" '</span>\n\n==External links==\n*[http://mairangibay.blogspot.com/ Author's Homepage]\n*[http://headworx.eyesis.co.nz/author/rossj.php HeadworX Publishers website]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120616111947/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm Massey University website]\n*[http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/writers/rossjack.html NZ Bookcouncil website]\n*[http://titus.books.online.fr Titus Books website]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ross, Jack}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male novelists]]\n[[Category:New Zealand poets]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male poets]]\n[[Category:New Zealand male short story writers]]\n[[Category:Massey University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Auckland alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century short story writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century New Zealand male writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century New Zealand male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n'''Jack Ross''' (born 6 November 1962 in [[Auckland]]), is a New Zealand poet, novelist, translator, editor and lecturer in creative writing.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm |title=Jack Ross \u2013 Massey University |work=massey.ac.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120616111947/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm |archive-date=16 June 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> A trilogy of novels has been published by two different publishers, [[Alan Brunton]]'s Bumper Books (Volume 1) and [[Titus Books (publisher)|Titus Books]].\n\n==Biography==\nBorn on Auckland's [[North Shore City|North Shore]], Ross was raised and educated in the [[East Coast Bays]]. After completing degrees in English and Italian at the [[University of Auckland]], Ross was given a [[Commonwealth Scholarship]] to study in the UK in<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/writers/rossjack.html |title=New Zealand Book Council |work=bookcouncil.org.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref> and was awarded a PhD in English and Comparative Literature by the [[University of Edinburgh]]. He is a Lecturer specialising in Academic and Creative Writing at [[Massey University]]'s Albany campus.\n\nFrom 2002 to 2005 Ross was editor of the literary magazine ''brief''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=757741 |title=brief |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120714152326/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=757741 |archive-date=14 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He has also edited other literary magazines ''The Pander'' (co-editor 1998\u201399),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=337755 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120715141644/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=337755 |url-status=dead |archive-date=15 July 2012 |title=The Pander |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 }}</ref> ''Spin'' (co-editor 1999\u20132003),<ref>{{cite web |url=http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=452127 |title=Spin : the quarterly magazine of Poetry Orbital Workshops. |work=nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711204655/http://nlnzcat.natlib.govt.nz/cgi-bin/Pwebrecon.cgi?BBID=452127 |archive-date=11 July 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> ''[[Landfall (journal)|Landfall]]'' (guest editor: issue 214, 2007),<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/landfall214.html |title=Landfall 212. 'The Capital of Nowhere', Edited by Richard Reeve Otago University Press, New Zealand |work=otago.ac.nz |year=2008 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref> and ''Poetry NZ'' (guest editor: issue 38, 2008).<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.poetrynz.net/archives/issue-38/ |title=Poetry New Zealand: Issue 38  |work=poetrynz.net |year=2011 |accessdate=25 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Criticism==\n\nRoss is little known outside New Zealand avante garde literary circles. He was described by [[Richard Reeve (poet)|Richard Reeve]] in ''[[Landfall (journal)|Landfall]]'' as \"a leading contributor to the field of experimental writing in New Zealand\",<ref>http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/forthcomingissue.html</ref> Mark Houlahan remarked in ''New Zealand Books'' [15 (2) (June 2005): 14\u201315], that \"Nobody else in New Zealand writes quite like Ross, though some of [[Bill Manhire]]'s fictions in ''The New Land'' are precedents.\" Other reviewers have been less positive: [[Laurence Jenkins]] wrote that \"Not all the contents are evil, but the spirit of darkness certainly prevails,\" about ''Nights with Giordano Bruno'' [in JAAM 16 (2001): 185]. According to [[Joe Wylie]] \"Outside of literati farm, this sort of thing has a very limited life expectancy ... Can Ross move beyond this? Does he choose not to?\" [Takahe 54 (2005) 63].\n\n==Works==\n* ''City of Strange Brunettes''. {{ISBN|0-473-05446-9}} (Auckland: Pohutukawa Press, 1998) [poems]\n* (with Gabriel White) ''A Town like Parataxis''. {{ISBN|0-473-07104-5}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2000) [poems / photos] [http://mairangibay.blogspot.com/2008/10/town-like-parataxis.html]\n* ''Nights with Giordano Bruno''. {{ISBN|0-9582225-0-9}} (Wellington: Bumper Books, 2000) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 1)] [http://www.crywolfbooks.org/bruno.php]\n* (with Gabriel White) ''The Perfect Storm''. {{ISBN|0-473-07350-1}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2000) [poems / video]\n* ''The Writing Skills Workshop''. prod. Robert van der Vyver (Otago University: Higher Education Development Centre, 2001) [workbook / video]\n* ''Chantal's Book''. {{ISBN|0-473-08744-8}} (Wellington: HeadworX, 2002) [poems] [http://headworx.eyesis.co.nz/poetry/chantal.php]\n* ''Monkey Miss Her Now''. {{ISBN|0-476-00182-X}} (Auckland: Danger Publishing, 2004) [short stories]\n* ''Trouble in Mind''. {{ISBN|0-9582586-1-9}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2005) [novella] [https://web.archive.org/web/20061202010251/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/Trouble.html]\n* ''A Bus Called Mr Nice Guy''. {{ISBN|0-473-10526-8}} (Auckland: Perdrix Press, 2005) [poems / travelogue]\n* ''The Imaginary Museum of Atlantis''. {{ISBN|0-9582586-8-6}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2006) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 2)] [https://web.archive.org/web/20070819044234/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/Atlantis.html]\n* ''To Terez\u00edn''. Social and Cultural Studies, 8. ISSN 1175-7132 (Auckland: Massey University, 2007) [poems / travelogue] [http://readingthemaps.blogspot.com/2007/06/to-terezin-and-back.html]\n*  ''Papyri: Love Poems & Fragments from Sappho''. {{ISBN|978-0-473-12397-0}} (Auckland: Soapbox Press, 2007)\n* ''EMO''. {{ISBN|978-1-877441-07-3}} (Auckland: Titus Books, 2008) [novel (R.E.M. Trilogy, 3)]<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://titus.books.online.fr/html/EMO.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=13 October 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110721015102/http://titus.books.online.fr/html/EMO.html |archive-date=21 July 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* ''The Return of the Vanishing New Zealander''. {{ISBN|978-0-9864507-6-1}}. (Dunedin: Kilmog Press, 2009) [poems]\n* ''Kingdom of Alt''. {{ISBN|978-1-877441-15-8}}. (Auckland: Titus Books, 2010) [short stories / novella]\n\nJack Ross has also edited and co-edited a number of publications.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* <span id=\"ref_Massey\">University of Massey Staff Page [https://web.archive.org/web/20120616111947/http://www.massey.ac.nz/massey/learning/departments/school-english-media-studies/staff/en/jack-ross.cfm \"Jack Ross]\" '</span>\n* <span id=\"ref_RossLandfall\">Landfall Web Page [http://www.otago.ac.nz/press/landfall/forthcomingissue.html \"Forthcoming Issue]\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_ReadingTheMaps\">Reading The Maps [http://readingthemaps.blogspot.com/2006/12/more-on-shore.html \"More On Shore]\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_Houlahan\">New Zealand Books 15 (2) (June 2005): 14\u201315\" '</span> \n* <span id=\"ref_Massey\">[[New Zealand Book Council]] [http://www.bookcouncil.org.nz/writers/rossjack.html \"Jack Ross]\" '</span>\n\n==